    "recap_headline": "University of Southern Mississippi Athletics",
    "recap_text": "JONESBORO, Ark. \u2013\nDavis Gillespie\ndrove in three runs and\nGrayden Harris\nthrew six shutout innings to lead No. 7 Southern Miss to a 7-1 Sun Belt Conference victory over Arkansas State Saturday evening at Tomlinson Stadium.\nThe Golden Eagles (16-3 overall, 1-1 Sun Belt) evened the series after dropping an 8-5 decision Friday night.\nGillespie gave the visitors the early advantage in the top of the first. After a one-out walk to\nMatthew Russo\n, Gillespie homered to the opposite field as his fourth round-tripper went over the right field wall for an early 2-0 advantage.\nMeanwhile, Harris limited the Red Wolves (14-6, 1-1) to just six hits over six innings and fanned four with no walks to get the victory and improve to 4-0.\nThe Golden Eagles added to their lead with a solo run in the sixth.\nBen Higdon\n, who reached base four times with a single, a double and two walks, drew a free pass to open the inning. The Red Wolves went to the bullpen in relief of starter Jack Nelson.\nDrey Barrett\nthen singled to right, sending Higdon to third. He scored one batter later when\nKyle Morrison\ngrounded into a double play.\nNelson allowed three runs on five hits with two walks and nine strikeouts to suffer the loss and fall to 1-2.\nSouthern Miss added four insurance runs in the ninth to pull away in the contest. After a flyout to center to open the inning,\nTucker Stockman\nwalked. After a\nSeth Smith\nsingle, his second of the night, freshman\nGray Eubanks\ndrove in his first collegiate run with his first hit, a single up the middle.\nJoey Urban\nthen walked to load the bases.\nThe Red Wolves then went to their third pitcher of the inning, who issued a bases-loaded walk to Russo in the only batter he faced. The final and fourth Red Wolves pitcher in the ninth got Gillespie to hit into an RBI fielder's choice and Higdon then doubled in a run before getting out of the frame.\nJosh Och\n, who entered for the Golden Eagles to start the eighth, fanned three over two innings with his only blemish being a solo home run to pinch hitter Cason Campbell.\nCamden Clark\nthen retired all three batters he faced in the ninth with one strikeout.\nThe deciding game of this series takes place on Sunday at 12 noon. The start time was moved up an hour due to expected bad weather in the area. The contest can be seen via ESPN+ as well as heard on an affiliate of the Southern Miss Sports Network."
  },
